<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> If a gamma ray hit an iron atom in the pusher plate, it would probably cause it to loose an electron. Now, if all of the iron atoms in the plate ionize like this, I don't know how that will effect plate performance.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It’s quite simple – the iron would destabilize and eventually become useless for its intended purpose.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Also, why would the plasma stick to the pusher plate?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Not stick really, but some of it would remain in contact with the pusher plate long enough to cause damage and perhaps long enough before the next pulse hit the plate. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>On a releated note, what are reactor vessels usually made out of?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Definitely not the same materials as Orion’s pusher plate. Plasma in reactors is usually held in place with magnets and rarely comes in contact with the containers materials.<br>
<br>
<br>
John Fraz<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> You've not even tried, it appears that you don't even know the works cited in the original article which started the thread on SDC.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I am refuting the Pseudoscience surrounding the nuclear devices and the pusher plate assembly. Sure, the whole concept of Orion is very nice, and according to the results from the Putt-Putt model, it might work. But until proper tests are completed with nuclear devices (NOT chemical), the whole thing is pure speculation.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> How about the bit about the fireball of a .1KT bomblet being outrun &amp; outdistanced by the plasma jet (supposition, yes), and the 20KT bombs being used only in vacuum, where there's no fireball of ionized air?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Fine, lets say for example Orion was built and launched in space. High-energy radiation in the form of photons emitted from the nuclear devices will most likely degrade the pusher plate quickly enough to make it unusable. Radiation will continue to degrade the Orion vehicle itself eventually killing everyone aboard. Radiation doesn’t just immediately go away. That should be simple enough to understand.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> (BTW, where do we get the idea that the shaped &amp; directed plasma jets are carriers of Gamma rays and other hard penetrating radiation which could damage the metal plate?)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Uh-nuclear detonations. Look it up yourself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Somebody have the book by G.Dyson? I'll bet money that he's got it cited when the decision was made, and the feelings now, over the technical feasibility.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
So, in other words, you don’t know. I’ll see your bet and raise you that those scientists at NASA looked over the studies and realized the very obvious – nuclear detonations cause a lot of damage. I think those boys who developed Orion were so overwhelmed with the concept; they ignored the effects of nuclear detonations. The guys at NASA weren’t so easily fooled.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> (I've already admitted that it's beyond my math, but it does seem to be accepted by the engineering/physics community</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
It’s not beyond my math. I’ve crunched enough numbers based on what I’ve found regarding nuclear detonations to understand that this bird is a disaster waiting to happen. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Tim<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> 1. I do understand basic nuclear physics, and<br>
I also understand basic nuclear weaponry.<br>
2. I do not claim to be state of the art in these<br>
fields, but I do understand the nuclear physics, and<br>
the nuclear weapon technology of the 1960s,<br>
and the 1970s.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Then you must have sat down and worked the numbers through, right? You must have come to the same conclusions as the boys at NASA, right? You must understand the effects of radiation have on materials, right?<br>
<br>
<br>
Zaphod<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> No. No one 'knows' for certain that an 'External Pulsed Plasma Propulsion' system would work. Experts believe that it could work.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I also believe that the concept would work as well – the Putt-Putt model was successful. The issues I have are with the effects of nuclear detonations on materials. Most here seem to be ignoring that major problem.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Members at this board believe the experts, and some think that actual hardware testing should be performed to validate the 'paper version'.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Agreed. I think it would be very difficult to test the continuous exposure to materials from continuous nuclear detonations – but in my opinion, this will be the deciding factor.<br>
<br>
