<br>
A lot of military projects have failed and been made public. What seems more likely: a minor project with consiting of studies and small labritory experiments is neffariously covered up to prevent the public from seeing that the government wasted mearly $10 million over ten years (not much for the DoD even then), or that they do not want to release information on how to make small bombs with reduced amounts of nuclear material?<br>
<br>
When they are refering to radiation, they are talking about exposure to the crew, not the ship. This is clear by compairing it to details in the reports, such as the 1963-5 NASA study I have (availible from NASA if you want a copy). The ship's structure provides shielding to the crew from radiation from the bombs (which could be a problem if you have insufficient shielding), thus a larger ship shields the crew more.<br>
<br>
Reactor containment vessels are exposed to intense neutron bombardment continuously for decades. Neutrons are more likely to transmut materials then Gammas, yet the containment vessels stay sound. The fact is that absorbtion is fairly rare for most materials, and ionization is not complete throughout a material after short term exposures. Most of the bomb's radiation would not encounter the ship, only a small portion would be projected toward the ship (that which traveled down the arc of the radiation channel). The people at General Atomic knew that some of the material would activate and would provide a threat for the crew if they entered the engine too soon after operation, but that activity levels would die down to safe levels in a few hours as the nuclides produced would have short half-lives. Thus they chose to build the ship out of materials which would activate into short lived nuclides. Over time the pusher plate would degrade from plasma and radiation, but it could be replaced when wear became too great.<br>
<br>
And it seems like you have some basic information on radioactive decay. I don't get what point you are making here.<br>
